<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05118k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05118k">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05118k"> 118(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> morals change</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In the English monasteries the Irish rule continued to be followed long after Colman turned his back on the country and went to Ireland. Thus it is noted concerning Ceolwulf, to whom Bede dedicated his <cite>Historia Ecclesiatica</cite> and who died in retirement in 760, that &ldquo;when this king became a monk <mark>license was given to the brethren to drink wine and beer</mark>; for down to that time water and milk alone had been permitted them, according to the rule of St. Aidan.&rdquo; <small> Benedict Fitzpatrick, <a name="IIMB" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#IIMB"><cite title="source">Ireland and the Making of Britain</cite></a> (1922) Britain 284</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
